	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date><add>&#63;</add> 19. 1857</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">My Dear friend&#58;&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Yours of the <date>4th of Nov.</date> &#38; enclosed commu&#45;<lb/>nication from <persName>Dr. Finskel</persName>&#44; has been duly re&#45;<lb/>ceived.  I have&#44; in accordance with your request&#44;<lb/> presented <persName>Dr. F&#39;s</persName> letter &#38; likewise your own<lb/> to the President of the Congregation &#8220;Emanu&#95;El&#44;&#8221; by<lb/> whom the proper attention was paid to it.  The<lb/> President&#44; <persName>Mr. L. Tichener</persName>&#44; on behalf of the<lb/> congregation requests me to return many<lb/> thanks to you for your trouble in the endeavor<lb/> of procuring a minister.  I have to ask<lb/> your pardon in delaying to answer your letter&#44;<lb/> the cause of which is that I have been un&#45;<lb/>usually busy.&#8212;The Congregation has received<lb/> now two applications&#95;one from <persName>Dr. Hoelzel</persName><lb/> now at <placeName>Australia</placeName>&#44; the other from a <persName>Rev Cohn</persName><lb/> now at <placeName><sic>Albani</sic></placeName>&#59; as no general meeting has<lb/> of late occurred&#44; no action had been<lb/> taken upon these applications.  According to<lb/> the occidents &#38; statements by the Heb. Journal<lb/> &#40;the Chronicle&#95;I believe&#41; shown to me&#44; &#38; various<lb/> other proofs&#44; I conclude that <persName>Dr. H.</persName> must be a<lb/> competent and suitable minister of <persName>Rev. Cohn</persName> I<lb/> have nothing heard&#44; but undoubtedly you are<lb/> acquainted with that gentleman.</p>
				<p><persName>Mr. H. Bien&#39;s</persName> term of office expires in about</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>five weeks.  At the regular meeting that was<lb/> some time since held for the purpose of electing<lb/> a Minister <persName>Mr. Bien</persName> has not handed in any<lb/> application for that office.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Another Jewish Journal called the &#8220;Gleaner&#8221;<lb/> under the editorship of <persName>Dr. Julias Eckman</persName><lb/> has last <date>Friday</date> made its appearance.&#8212;<lb/> I will send you a copy&#8212;Thus making five Hebrew sheets in <hi rend="underline">this city</hi>.</p>
				<p>I have of late not given to you any news&#44;<lb/> thinking it unnecessary&#44; as we have<lb/> now Jewish papers published here&#44; &#38; such<lb/> news&#44; that are of any importance&#44; you<lb/> can therefore extract from them.  But should<lb/> you prefer&#44; to have them few news occur&#45;<lb/>&#45;ring here communicated by myself&#44;<lb/> I will do the same with pleasure.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am anxiously awaiting the &#8220;advocate&#44;&#8221;<lb/> &#38; then I hope to procure a good number<lb/> of subscribers for it</p>
				<p>In compliance with your wish&#44; I return<lb/> you enclosed <persName>Dr. Frankel&#39;s</persName> Letter.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">with many wishes for Your Prosperity</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">Cauffman H. M<add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
		</body>
